Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Grate the @ginger{½}.

Heat a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Once hot, add the @lamb mince{200%g}. Fry until the lamb is nicely browned, breaking it up with a #wooden spoon{} as it cooks, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir in the onion and cook until, stirring occasionally, ~{5%minutes}. Add the @North Indian style spice mix{1}, @tomato puree{30%g} and the garlic and ginger and cook for ~{1%minute} more, stirring continuously. Add the @raisins{40%g} and @basmati rice{150%g} to the lamb mixture.

Pour in the @water{300%ml} and bring to the boil. When boiling, add the @chicken stock paste{10}, stir, then lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to simmer for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

> The rice will continue to cook in its own steam while the pan is covered - don't remove the lid early.

While the rice cooks, trim the @green beans{150%g} and chop into thirds.

> Then you can put your feet up for a bit!

Ten mins before the biryani is cooked, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the green beans and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir together and cook until the beans are softened and slightly charred, ~{5-6%minutes}. Remove the pan from the heat.

When the biryani is cooked, fluff up the rice with a #fork{} then stir in the green beans. Taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it. Serve the biryani in #bowls{} with a spoonful of @low fat natural yoghurt{150%g} on top. Enjoy!